\begin_layout Standard
where the extreme points of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 are
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\boldsymbol{a}_{1} & =(0,0)\\
\boldsymbol{a}_{2} & =(0,5)\\
\boldsymbol{a}_{3} & =(2,5)\\
\boldsymbol{a}_{4} & =(5,2)\\
\boldsymbol{a}_{5} & =(5,0)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{2}$
\end_inset

 are linear, we can determine where 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{2}$
\end_inset

 are maximized by evaluating them at the extreme points and comparing them
 with each other.
 We find that 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}$
\end_inset

 is maximized at 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}_{4}$
\end_inset

 with maximum objective value being 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1}^{I}:=f_{1}(\boldsymbol{a}_{4})=17$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{2}$
\end_inset

 is maximized at 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}_{3}$
\end_inset

 with maximum objective value being 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{2}^{I}:=f_{2}(\boldsymbol{a}_{3})=12$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore the ideal point is 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{y}^{I}=(y_{1}^{I},y_{2}^{I})=(17,12)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2.
 The weighted norm problem is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\text{minimize} & \quad\frac{1}{4}(17-3x_{1}-x_{2})+\frac{3}{4}(12-x_{1}-2x_{2})\\
\text{subject to} & \quad\boldsymbol{x}\in X.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

We can simplify this as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\text{minimize} & \quad\frac{1}{4}(53-6x_{1}-7x_{2})\\
\text{subject to} & \quad\boldsymbol{x}\in X.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Since the objective is linear and the feasible set is bounded and convex,
 we can determine where the objective is minimized by evaluating it at the
 extreme points and comparing each value with each other.
 We find that the objective has a unique minimizer at 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}_{3}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
3.
 The weighted norm problem is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\text{minimize} & \quad\left(\frac{1}{4}(17-3x_{1}-x_{2})^{2}+\frac{3}{4}(12-x_{1}-2x_{2})^{2}\right)^{1/2}\\
\text{subject to} & \quad\boldsymbol{x}\in X.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

The optimal solutions to this problem will be the same as the optimal solutions
 to the following problem:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\text{minimize} & \quad\frac{1}{4}(17-3x_{1}-x_{2})^{2}+\frac{3}{4}(12-x_{1}-2x_{2})^{2}\\
\text{subject to} & \quad\boldsymbol{x}\in X.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Indeed, this follow from the fact that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\psi(\boldsymbol{x}):=\frac{1}{4}(17-3x_{1}-x_{2})^{2}+\frac{3}{4}(12-x_{1}-2x_{2})^{2}
\]

\end_inset

is always nonnegatve, being a sum of two squares.
 A quick calculation shows that, among the extreme points, 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 is minimized at 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}_{4}$
\end_inset

 with objective value given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(\boldsymbol{a}_{4})=27/4$
\end_inset

.
 We claim that 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}_{4}$
\end_inset

 is the unique minimizer to the problem.
 Indeed, first note that the gradient of 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}_{4}$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\nabla\psi(\boldsymbol{x})\Big|_{\boldsymbol{x}=\boldsymbol{a}_{4}}=\begin{pmatrix}\frac{3}{2}(4x_{1}+3x_{2}-29)\\
\frac{1}{2}(9x_{1}+13x_{2}-89)
\end{pmatrix}\Big|_{\boldsymbol{x}=\boldsymbol{a}_{4}}=\begin{pmatrix}-9/2\\
-9
\end{pmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset

Furthermore, the tangent line of the level set 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\psi=27/4\}$
\end_inset

 at the point 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}_{4}$
\end_inset

 is precisely the blue line given by the equation 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}+x_{2}=7$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, since 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 is globally strictly convex with positive Hessian and since the direction
 
\begin_inset Formula $(-9/2,-9)^{\top}$
\end_inset

 points towards the feasible set from 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, we see that moving along any direction from 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}_{4}$
\end_inset

 to another point in the feasible set 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 will only increase the objective.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}_{4}$
\end_inset

 is the unique minimizer to our problem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
4.
 The weighted norm problem is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\text{minimize} & \quad\max\left\{ \frac{1}{4}(17-3x_{1}-x_{2}),\frac{3}{4}(12-x_{1}-2x_{2})\right\} \label{eq:max0}\\
\text{subject to} & \quad\boldsymbol{x}\in X.\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

Set 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}(\boldsymbol{x})=\frac{1}{4}(17-3x_{1}-x_{2})$
\end_inset

 and set 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{2}(\boldsymbol{x})=\frac{3}{4}(12-x_{1}-2x_{2})$
\end_inset

.
 Observe that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
g_{1}(\boldsymbol{x})\geq g_{2}(\boldsymbol{x}) & \iff\frac{1}{4}(17-3x_{1}-x_{2})\geq\frac{3}{4}(12-x_{1}-2x_{2})\\
 & \iff17-3x_{1}-x_{2}\geq36-3x_{1}-6x_{2}\\
 & \iff x_{2}\geq19/5.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

In particular, if 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}\leq19/5$
\end_inset

, then the problem becomes
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\text{minimize} & \quad\frac{1}{4}(17-3x_{1}-x_{2})\label{eq:max1}\\
\text{subject to} & \quad\boldsymbol{x}\in X_{\leq19/5}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{\leq19/5}=X\cap\{x_{2}\leq19/5\}$
\end_inset

.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{\leq19/5}$
\end_inset

 has the same extreme points as 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 except we replace 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}_{2}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{b}_{2}=(0,19/5)$
\end_inset

 and we replace 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}_{3}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{b}_{3}=(16/5,19/5)$
\end_inset

.
 After evaluating and comparing the objective at the extreme points, we
 find that 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:max1})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 has a unique minimizer at 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}_{4}$
\end_inset

 with objective value being 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

.
 On the other hand, if 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}\geq19/5$
\end_inset

, then the problem becomes
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\text{minimize} & \frac{3}{4}(12-x_{1}-2x_{2})\label{eq:max1-1}\\
\text{subject to} & \quad\boldsymbol{x}\in X_{\geq19/5}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{\geq19/5}=X\cap\{x_{2}\geq19/5\}$
\end_inset

.
 Note that the extreme points of 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{\geq19/5}$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}_{2}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}_{3}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{b}_{2}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{b}_{3}$
\end_inset

.
 After evaluating and comparing the objective at the extreme points, we
 find that 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:max1-1})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 has a unique minimizer at 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}_{4}$
\end_inset

 with objective value being 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

.
 Altogether, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\boldsymbol{a}_{3},\boldsymbol{a}_{4}\}$
\end_inset

 is the set of all optimal solutions to 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:max0})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

