\begin_layout Section*
Problem 5
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{ex}
\backslash
label{ex}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Consider the lexicographic method and prove the following: If 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}^{*}\in X$
\end_inset

 is an optimal solution to problem 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{P}(\Pi(p))$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}^{*}$
\end_inset

 is an efficient solution to the MOP.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{ex}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{sol}
\backslash
label{sol}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Assume for a contradiction that 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}^{*}\in X$
\end_inset

 is an optimal solution to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{P}(\Pi(p))$
\end_inset

 but is not efficient to the MOP.
 Then there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}\in X$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\boldsymbol{x})\le f(\boldsymbol{x}^{*})$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, there exists some 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in\{1,\dots,p\}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}(\boldsymbol{x})<f_{i}(\boldsymbol{x}^{*})$
\end_inset

.
 Set
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
i_{0}:=\min\{i\mid f_{i}(\boldsymbol{x})<f_{i}(\boldsymbol{x}^{*})\}.
\]

\end_inset

Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}(\boldsymbol{x})=f_{i}(\boldsymbol{x}^{*})$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,\dots,i_{0}-1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i_{0}}(\boldsymbol{x})<f_{i_{0}}(\boldsymbol{x}^{*})$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\boldsymbol{x})<_{\mathrm{lex}}f(\boldsymbol{x}^{*})$
\end_inset

 which contradicts our assumption that 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}^{*}$
\end_inset

 an optimal solution to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{P}(\Pi(p))$
\end_inset

.
 Note that the same argument holds if we permute the indices by any permutation
 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\in S_{p}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{sol}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

